The '''thirteenth season''' of '''''[[South Park]]''''', an American animated television comedy series, originally aired in the United States on [[Comedy Central]] between March 11 and November 18, 2009. The season was headed by the series creators [[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]], who served as [[executive producer]]s along with Anne Garefino. The season continued to focus on the exploits of protagonists [[Stan Marsh|Stan]], [[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]], [[Eric Cartman|Cartman]], [[Kenny McCormick|Kenny]] and [[Butters Stotch|Butters]] in the fictional [[Colorado]] mountain town of South Park.

The season was the first of three new seasons Parker and Stone agreed to produce for the network under a renewal deal. It consisted of fourteen 22-minute episodes, which aired in two groups of seven episodes separated by a six-month gap. Prior to the season's premiere, all ''South Park'' episodes were made available for free viewing on the official series website, ''South Park Studios''. The thirteenth season was the first to be broadcast in [[High-definition television|high definition]] and in widescreen. Continuing their practice from previous seasons, Parker and Stone wrote and produced each episode within the week before its broadcast date.

The thirteenth season satirized such topics as the [[ACORN 2009 undercover videos controversy|ACORN scandal]], [[Whaling in Japan|Japanese whaling]], [[piracy in Somalia]] and the marketing tactics of the [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney Company]]. Celebrities were spoofed throughout the season, including the [[Jonas Brothers]], [[Kanye West]], [[Carlos Mencia]], [[Paul Watson]] and [[Glenn Beck]], all of whom publicly responded to their portrayals. The episode "[[Fishsticks (South Park)|Fishsticks]]" attracted particular media attention due to rapper Kanye West's declaration that its jokes about his arrogance were funny but hurt his feelings. "[[The F Word (South Park)|The F Word]]", in which the central characters attempt to change the definition of the word "[[faggot (slang)|fag]]", was especially controversial and prompted complaints from the [[Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]]. A broadcast of "[[Pinewood Derby (South Park)|Pinewood Derby]]" in Mexico was pulled, allegedly due to its depiction of [[President of Mexico|Mexican President]] [[Felipe Calder<U+00F3>n]]. "[[Fatbeard]]" was praised by the crew of the [[USS Bainbridge (DDG-96)|USS ''Bainbridge'']], which was involved in the [[Maersk Alabama hijacking|2009 rescue]] of the [[MV Maersk Alabama|MV ''Maersk Alabama'']] from Somalian pirates.

The thirteenth season received mixed reviews: some critics called it one of ''South Park''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s strongest seasons, while others claimed the series was starting to decline in quality. The season maintained the average [[Nielsen ratings|Nielsen rating]] viewership for the series, around 3&nbsp;million viewers per episode. The episode "[[Margaritaville (South Park)|Margaritaville]]", which satirized the [[Late-2000s recession|global recession]] then affecting much of the industrialized world, won the 2009 [[Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program (for Programming Less Than One Hour)|Outstanding Animated Program (for Programming Less Than One Hour)]].

