==Production==
===Crew===
[[File:Trey Parker Matt Stone 2007.jpg|thumb|260px|right|''South Park'' co-creators [[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]] served as executive producers for the thirteenth season.|alt=Two seated men. One holds a microphone in one hand and gestures with the other.]]
Series creators [[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]] were the executive producers of the thirteenth season of ''South Park'', along with Anne Garefino. The season was distributed by [[Comedy Central]], where the series has aired since its inception in 1997. Frank C. Agnone II served as supervising producer, while [[Eric Stough]], [[Adrien Beard]], [[Vernon Chatman]], Bruce Howell and Erica Rivinoja worked as producers.<ref name="Moody">{{cite web |last=Moody |first=Annemarie |publisher=[[Animation World Network]] |date=March 10, 2009 |title=Jonas Brothers Bring Purity to South Park in 13th Season Premiere |url=http://www.awn.com/news/television/jonas-brothers-bring-purity-south-park-13th-season-premiere |accessdate=February 16, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4nmmdlC |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name="EmmyWinners">{{Cite web |title=Primetime Emmy Award Database: Outstanding Animated Program (for Programming Less Than One Hour) - 2009 |publisher=[[Emmy Award|Emmy.com]] |year=2009 |url=http://www.emmys.com/award_history_search?person=&program=south+park&start_year=2009&end_year=2009&network=All&web_category=All&winner=All  |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4nt3RJr |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' cast member [[Bill Hader]], who had previously worked as a consultant on the show, was credited as a producer starting in season thirteen. Hader said of his role with the show, "It's really Trey and Matt who kind of write everything, and you're just in the room kind of helping them. Basically, I'm friends with them and they're just nice enough to invite me into the room and let me goof around."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Toal |first=Drew |title=The Hot Seat: Bill Hader |work=[[Time Out (company)|Time Out]] |date=March 26, 2009}}</ref> Ryan Quincy served as director of animation during the thirteenth season.<ref name="EmmyWinners" />

===Development===
''South Park'' was set to expire in 2008, but in August 2007 it was announced the series would be renewed for at least three more seasons, extending it through 2011.  The new seasons, thirteen, [[South Park (season 14)|fourteen]] and fifteen, were each to consist of fourteen episodes. Stone said of the announcement, "Three more years of ''South Park'' will give us the opportunity to offend that many more people."<ref name="IGN0827">{{Cite web |title=South Park Gets Three More Seasons |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=August 27, 2007 |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/816/816143p1.html |accessdate=February 16, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4nzdC1W |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name="CC0827">{{Cite news |title="South Park" creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone agree to three-year extension of "South Park" and form comprehensive production and development joint venture with Comedy Central to create South Park Digital Studios |url=http://www.comedycentral.com/press/press_releases/2007/082707_southpark_extension_jv.jhtml |publisher=[[Comedy Central]] |date=August 27, 2007 |accessdate=February 16, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4oLPeNb |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> Parker and Stone also announced they would partner with Comedy Central to create a Los Angeles<U+2013>based digital animation studio called South Park Digital Studios, which would serve as the center for all digital extensions of the ''South Park'' franchise and other animated projects.<ref name="IGN0827" />

Prior to the broadcast of the thirteenth season, Parker and Stone made every episode from the previous twelve seasons of ''South Park'' available for free viewing on the official series website, ''South Park Studios''. New episodes from the thirteenth season were made available for one week after the original airdate, then removed for thirty days, after which they were returned to the site permanently. The episodes were uncensored and ad-supported, so no membership fees were required to view the shows. In a statement, Parker and Stone said, "We got really sick of having to download our own show illegally all the time. So we gave ourselves a legal alternative."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lewinski |first=John Scott |title=''South Park'' to Offer All Episodes Free |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=March 26, 2008 |url=http://www.wired.com/underwire/2008/03/south-park-to-o/ |accessdate=February 16, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4oRLGzs |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Thielman |first=Sam |title="South Park" site offers every episode |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=March 25, 2008 |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117982893.html?categoryid=14&cs=1&nid=2570 |accessdate=February 16, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4oZK1AG |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Spring |first=Tom |work=[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]] |date=March 25, 2008 |title=South Park Opens Vault: Allows Free and Full Episode Access Online |url=http://blogs.pcworld.com/staffblog/archives/006691.html |accessdate=February 16, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4ocqfD6 |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref>

Two months before the thirteenth season premiered, ''South Park Studios'' announced that it would be the first season to be broadcast in [[high-definition television|high definition]] and presented in widescreen. Episodes from previous seasons were also converted to high definition.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Goldman |first=Eric |title=South Park Now in HD |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=January 13, 2009 |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/944/944487p1.html |accessdate=February 16, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4of0iUt |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> The season's episodes first aired in the United States on Wednesdays at 10&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Standard Time]] on Comedy Central, and were repeated Wednesdays at 12&nbsp;a.m., Thursdays at 10&nbsp;p.m. and 12&nbsp;a.m., and Sundays at 11&nbsp;p.m. and 2&nbsp;a.m., all EST. The first seven episodes of the season aired from March 11, 2009, premiering with "[[The Ring (South Park)|The Ring]]",<ref name="Moody" /> and ended on April 22 with the mid-season finale "[[Fatbeard]]".<ref name="IGN0423">{{Cite web |last=Fickett |first=Travis |title=South Park: "Fatbeard" Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=April 23, 2009 |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/975/975751p1.html |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4ojB4cJ |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> The season returned with seven more episodes, resuming on October 7 with "[[Dead Celebrities]]",<ref name="IGN1008">{{Cite web |last=Isler |first=Ramsey |title=South Park: "Dead Celebrities" Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=October 8, 2009 |url=http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/103/1033150p1.html |accessdate=January 11, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4otVzxt |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> and ending on November 18 with the season finale, "[[Pee (South Park)|Pee]]".<ref name="IGN0312">{{Cite web |last=Fickett |first=Travis |title=South Park: "The Ring" Review <U+2013> The Jonas Bros. come to Colorado, ruin Kenny's would-be sex life |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=March 12, 2009 |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/961/961804p1.html |accessdate=March 12, 2009 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4ozvGBc |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref>

===Writing===
Continuing their practice from previous seasons, Parker and Stone wrote and produced each episode within the week before its broadcast date, although as in previous seasons, only Trey Parker was listed as writer in the end credits. The duo conceived a list of episode ideas at the start of the season, but said they preferred to wait until the last minute to start working. Deadline pressure, they explained, energized them as if they were doing a live show. Stone said of the practice, "We kind of need that [chaos] to work. We're, like, 'We have to do something right now. It's going on the air in just a few minutes.'"<ref name="Morrow0312">{{Cite web |last=Morrow |first=Terry |title=Morrow TV: Looking at 'South Park' ... Other shows of note |publisher=[[E. W. Scripps Company|Scripps Howard News Services]] |date=March 12, 2009 |url=http://www.scrippsnews.com/node/41654 |accessdate=February 17, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4p2N9TC |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> For example, three days before the broadcast of the season premiere, "The Ring", the script was only half-finished and the animation was incomplete.<ref name="Morrow0312" /> Likewise, they did not start work on "Whale Whores" until five days before the episode aired,<ref>{{Cite video | people=[[Trey Parker|Parker, Trey]]| date=November 2010 |title=South Park: The Complete Thirteenth Season: "Whale Whores" |format=Audio commentary |medium= Blu-ray Disc|publisher=[[Paramount Pictures#Paramount Home Entertainment|Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> and the scripts for "[[Margaritaville (South Park)|Margaritaville]]" and "Pee" were both still being finished the day before the episodes were first broadcast.<ref>{{Cite video | people=[[Trey Parker|Parker, Trey]]| date=November 2010 |title=South Park: The Complete Thirteenth Season: "Margaritaville" |format=Audio commentary |medium= Blu-ray Disc|publisher=[[Paramount Pictures#Paramount Home Entertainment|Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite video | people=[[Trey Parker|Parker, Trey]]| date=November 2010 |title=South Park: The Complete Thirteenth Season: "Pee" |format=Audio commentary |medium= Blu-ray Disc|publisher=[[Paramount Pictures#Paramount Home Entertainment|Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Parker and Stone said "Dead Celebrities" was a particularly challenging episode to make<U+2014>they were up all night working on it the day before it aired, and did not finish until 11&nbsp;a.m. on its broadcast date.<ref>{{Cite video | people=[[Trey Parker|Parker, Trey]]| date=November 2010 |title=South Park: The Complete Thirteenth Season: "Dead Celebrities" |format=Audio commentary |medium= Blu-ray Disc|publisher=[[Paramount Pictures#Paramount Home Entertainment|Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Some critics have said that this short turnaround process helps ''South Park'' stay fresh and allows the show to address current events in a timely fashion.<ref name="IGN0423" />

The thirteenth season introduced the characters Katie and Katherine, stars of a television show, ''The Queef Sisters'', that consists largely of [[vaginal flatulence]] jokes. They are female equivalents of long-time characters [[List of supporting characters on South Park#Terrance and Phillip|Terrance and Phillip]], who are initially angered at the competition from Katie and Katherine, but end up romantically involved with them.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Modell |first=Josh |title="Eat, Pray, Queef" |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=April 2, 2009 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/eat-pray-queef,26087/ |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4pFwIiQ |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> Season thirteen also marked the final appearance of long-time supporting character [[List of students at South Park Elementary#Others|Gordon Stoltski]], the third grade student who read the morning announcements for South Park Elementary. In the episode "[[Dances with Smurfs]]", Gordon is murdered while reading the announcements by a gunman who mistakes him for a truck driver who slept with his wife. Some critics found the scene disturbing and inappropriate in the light of recent school shootings in the United States.<ref name="IGN1112">{{Cite web |url = http://tv.ign.com/articles/104/1044572p1.html |title="Dances with Smurfs" Review |last=Isler |first=Ramsey |date=November 12, 2009 |publisher=[[IGN]] | accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4pMNHWk |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref>

The running gag of [[Kenny McCormick#Deaths|killing protagonist Kenny McCormick]] continued, though he was killed only three times during the season: in the episode "The Ring", he contracts syphilis after engaging in oral sex;<ref name="IGN0312" /> in "W.T.F.", he is shot by a rocket launcher during a professional wrestling match;<ref name="AV2110">{{Cite web |last=Modell |first=Josh |title=W.T.F. |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=October 7, 2009 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/wtf,34408/ |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4pPnLdY |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> and in "Pee", he drowns in the urine that inundates the water park.<ref name="AVClub1111">{{Cite web |last=Isler |first=Ramsey |title=South Park: "Pee" Review |date=November 11, 2009 |publisher=[[IGN]] |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/104/1047593p1.html |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4pTZHK9 |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> During the final half of the season, aliens were hidden in images throughout the episodes as part of a contest offered by ''South Park Studios''. Viewers able to find the alien in the episode could enter a contest, with the grand winner getting an animated version of himself or herself placed in the ''South Park'' opening credits starting the next season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Become a South Park Citizen |date=October 4, 2009 |publisher=South Park Studios |url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/news/357474/become-a-south-park-citizen |accessdate=November 3, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4pdRYQ9 |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> In December 2009, Matthew Klinner was announced winner of the contest.<ref>{{Cite web |title=South Park Citizen Winners |date=December 18, 2009 |publisher=South Park Studios |url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/news/357516/south-park-citizen-winners |accessdate=November 3, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4plUmV3 |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref>

===Cultural references===
The thirteenth season also continued a ''South Park'' tradition of lampooning celebrities and timely issues. The episode "Margaritaville" satirized the [[Late-2000s recession|global recession]] affecting much of the industrialized world at the time of the episode's broadcast. Parker and Stone said they had long planned to do an episode about the recession, but did not want to rush it because they wanted to make sure the script was strong.<ref name="Morrow0312" /> "Fatbeard" was based on real-life [[piracy in Somalia]], which began receiving increasing international media attention in 2008; the Somali pirates are portrayed in a sympathetic light in the episode.<ref name="Flanagan">{{Cite news |last=Flanagan |first=Ben |title=Ben Around: "South Park: on a roll |date=May 1, 2009 |work=The Tuscaloosa News |location=[[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], [[Alabama]] |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20090501/NEWS/904309962/1005?Title=BEN-AROUND-South-Park-on-a-roll |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4pqpQHu |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name="Tucker0422">{{Cite news |last=Tucker |first=Ken |title="South Park" attacks Somalia and Susan Boyle |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=April 22, 2009 |url=http://watching-tv.ew.com/2009/04/south-park-atta.html |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4psyJNr |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> "Dances with Smurfs" parodied the political commentary of [[Glenn Beck]], a nationally syndicated radio show host and [[Fox News Channel]] political pundit.<ref name="AV1111">{{Cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/dances-with-smurfs,35286/ |title=South Park: Dances With Smurfs |last=O'Neal |first=Sean |date =November 11, 2009 |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4pvJVOB |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name="aol">{{Cite web |url=http://insidetv.aol.com/2009/11/12/south-park-episode-glenn-beck-sarah-palin/ | title="South Park" Episode Skewered Glenn Beck, Sarah Palin and Others |last=Deane |first=Donald |date=November 12, 2009 |publisher=[[AOL]] | accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4pxsApZ |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> In the episode, Cartman makes outrageous claims with no basis in fact under the guise that he is simply asking rhetorical questions and seeking further discussion, a practice for which Beck has been criticized.<ref name="IGN1112" /><ref name="AV1111" />

The episode "[[Whale Whores]]" addressed the controversies surrounding [[Whaling in Japan|Japanese whaling]], condemning not only the whalers who engaged in the practice, but shows like ''[[Whale Wars]]'' and activists like television celebrity Paul Watson who profit from fighting whaling.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Murphy |first=Dan |title=South Park puts spotlight on Paul Watson and his "Whale Wars" |work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |date=October 29, 2009 |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Global-News/2009/1029/south-park-puts-spotlight-on-paul-watson-and-his-whale-wars |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4q0MDGt |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=d'Estries |first=Michael |title=South Park "Whale Whores" Manages To Hilariously Offend Everyone Equally |date=October 29, 2009 |publisher=ecorazzi |url=http://www.ecorazzi.com/2009/10/29/south-park-whale-whores-manages-to-hilariously-offend-everyone-equally/ |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4q2b2NW |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> "[[Butters' Bottom Bitch]]" featured a scene in which [[Butters Stotch|Butters]] vists an [[Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now|ACORN]] office seeking benefits for prostitutes working for him, a reference to a similar [[ACORN 2009 undercover videos controversy|2009 scandal]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kohler |first=Chris |title=''Gay Tony''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Timely Jokes Justify Episodic Gaming |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=November 3, 2009 |url=http://www.wired.com/gamelife/2009/11/gay-tony/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4q7nRoR |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=GOP Calls on Obama to Fire Jennings |publisher=[[Fox News]] |last=Hannity |first=Sean |author-link=Sean Hannity |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,567643,00.html |accessdate=January 10, 2010 |date=February 17, 2009 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qA7VhR |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> The episode "[[Eat, Pray, Queef]]" demonstrated a double standard between rights of men and women by showing the South Park men, who have no problem with farting, strongly objecting to vaginal flatulence from women.<ref>{{Cite video | people=[[Trey Parker|Parker, Trey]]| date=November 2010 |title=South Park: The Complete Thirteenth Season: "Eat, Pray, Queef" |format=Audio commentary |medium= Blu-ray Disc|publisher=[[Paramount Pictures#Paramount Home Entertainment|Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref>  The season finale, "Pee", satirized the [[disaster film]] genre, especially the movie ''[[2012 (film)|2012]]'', which was released five days before the episode aired. Cartman interprets the large number of minorities at his favorite water park as a sign of the [[2012 phenomenon]], the prediction that cataclysmic events will occur in the year 2012, which is said to be the end of the [[Mesoamerican Long Count calendar|Mayan Long Count calendar]].<ref name="AVClub1111" /><ref name="AVClub1118" />

"The Ring" featured parodies of the pop-rock [[boy band]] Jonas Brothers and a foul-mouthed, greedy, physically violent [[Mickey Mouse]], satirizing the [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney Company]]'s exploitation of family-friendly morals to disguise its profit motive.<ref name="IGN0312" /><ref name="Flanagan" /><ref name="Time0312">{{Cite news |last=Poniewozik |first=James |title=Is South Park the Most Moral Show on TV? |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=March 12, 2009 |url=http://tunedin.blogs.time.com/2009/03/12/is-south-park-the-most-moral-show-on-tv/ |accessdate=March 12, 2009 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4rimvQS |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> "[[The Coon]]" served as a parody of dark-toned comic book movies, like ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' (2008), ''[[The Spirit (film)|The Spirit]]'' (2008) and ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]'' (2009).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Marshall |first=Rick |title="South Park" Superhero Parody Spoofs "Watchmen," "The Dark Knight" & Dark Comics Trend |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=March 19, 2009 |url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2009/03/19/south-park-superhero-parody-spoofs-watchmen-the-dark-knight-dark-comics-trend/ |accessdate=February 18, 2009 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4rlVZss |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Koski |first=Genevieve |title="The Coon" |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=March 18, 2009 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-coon,25317/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4rnRTCs |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> "Dead Celebrities" mocked numerous recently deceased celebrities, including [[Michael Jackson]], [[Billy Mays]] and [[David Carradine]], as well as the show ''[[Ghost Hunters]]''.<ref name="IGN1008" /><ref name="AVClub">{{Cite web |last=Modell |first=Josh |title=South Park: Dead Celebrities |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=October 7, 2009 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/dead-celebrities,33818/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4rqE439 |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> "Dances with Smurfs" mocked the 2009 [[James Cameron]] film ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'', suggesting the plot borrows heavily from the film ''[[Dances with Wolves]]'' and comparing Avatar's blue aliens to the cartoon [[The Smurfs|Smurfs]].<ref name="AV1111" /> The episode "[[W.T.F.]]" parodied professional wrestling in general and [[World Wrestling Entertainment]] in particular, highlighting the soap opera aspects of wrestling storylines and fans who believe the stories are real.<ref name="PWInsider">{{Cite web |last=Johnson |first=Mike |title=Vince McMahon Appears on South Park |date=October 22, 2009 |publisher=PWInsider.com |url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/42410/vince-mcmahon-appears-on-south-park.html?p=1 |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4ruaZM3 |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref>

===Music===
{{Listen
 |filename     = South Park Fishsticks Gay Fish.ogg
 |title        = "Gay Fish", an original song featured in the episode "Fishsticks"
 |description = <br>"Gay Fish" parodies [[Kanye West]]'s "[[Heartless (Kanye West song)|Heartless]]", particularly in its extravagant use of [[Auto-Tune]] pitch audio processing.
 |type         = music
 |pos          = right
}}
Several original songs written by Parker and Stone were featured in the thirteenth season. The episode "Fatbeard" features a song, "Somalian Pirates, We", in which Cartman and his crew of pirates sing in the style of the [[Golden Age of Piracy]].<ref name="PirateSong">{{Cite web |date=April 29, 2009 |title=News: The Pirate Song |url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/news/357455/the-pirate-song |publisher=[[South Park|South Park Studios]] |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4s5VDXt |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> In response to fan requests, the full 90-second version of the song was made available for download on ''South Park Studios'' the week the episode aired.<ref name="AVClub0422" /><ref name="PirateSong" /> The season finale, "Pee", features a tune sung by Cartman, "(Too Many Minorities) Not My Water Park", in which he despairs over the large number of African-American, Hispanic-American and Asian-American patrons at his water park. Among other topics, Cartman expresses his anger about long lines full of minorities and park employees speaking Spanish rather than English.<ref>{{Cite news |title=South Park's (Too Many Minorities) Not My Water Park [Video & Lyrics] |url=http://coedmagazine.com/2009/11/19/south-parks-too-many-minorities-not-my-water-park-video-lyrics/ |date=November 19, 2009 |work=CoEd Magazine |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4s8jsES |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> The episode "Eat, Pray, Queef" features "Queef Free", a charity single recorded by the men of ''South Park'' after they realize women should be free to queef just as men are free to fart. The song has been described as a parody of such celebrities-for-charity songs as "[[We Are The World]]".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Anderson |first=Thomas |title=Men Farting, Women Queefing |publisher=Screen Junkies |date=April 1, 2009 |url=http://www.screenjunkies.com/recap/men-farting-women-queefing |accessdate=May 10, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4sCHxRK |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref>

The thirteenth season also featured or spoofed real-life songs and bands. The episode "Fishsticks", which prominently featured rapper Kanye West, includes a two-and-a-half minute song, "Gay Fish", that parodies West's "[[Heartless (Kanye West song)|Heartless]]". "Gay Fish" satirizes the rapper's tendency to rely on audio processing to correct his mistakes in [[Pitch (music)|pitch]].<ref name="AVClub0422">{{Cite web |last=O'Neal |first=Sean |title=South Park: Season 13: Episode 7: "Fatbeard" |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=April 22, 2009 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/fatbeard,27043/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4ryE2OS |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Barrett |first=Annie |title="South Park": Kanye West is a gay fish, yo |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=April 9, 2009|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/popwatch/2009/04/south-park-fish.html |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4s0b6Rd |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> After "Fishsticks" aired, the full song was made available for download on ''South Park Studios''.<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 9, 2009 |title=News: The Gay Fish Song |url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/news/357444/the-gay-fish-song |publisher=[[South Park|South Park Studios]] |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4s2uQYn |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> Several fake Jonas Brothers songs, with lyrics about the band members' physical attractiveness, were written for "The Ring". Some songs also emphasize the band's belief in sexual abstinence, with lyrics like, "Who needs sex and drugs and partying when we can cook a meal and sit around and watch [[Netflix]]?"<ref name="IGN0312" /> The strongly erotic reactions of the young girls at their concert parody the frenzied female fan reactions the Jonas Brothers tend to elicit, even though their image projects wholesomeness and chastity.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tucker |first=Ken |title="South Park" saves the Jonas Brothers' souls | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=March 12, 2009 |url=http://watching-tv.ew.com/2009/03/12/south-park-jona/ |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4sG0Jce |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> In the episode "Whale Wars", Cartman plays the video game ''[[Rock Band]]'' and performs a rendition, praised by critics, of the [[Lady Gaga]] song "[[Poker Face (Lady Gaga song)|Poker Face]]".<ref>{{Cite web | title = "South Park" Takes On Lady Gaga's "Poker Face"| url = http://newsroom.mtv.com/2009/10/29/south-park-lady-gaga/ | first = Brian | last = Jacks | date = October 29, 2009 | publisher = [[MTV]] | accessdate = February 20, 2010 |archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5u4sI7YzB |archivedate = November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Isler |first=Ramsey |title=South Park: "Whale Whores" Review |date=October 29, 2009 |publisher=[[IGN]] |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/104/1040366p1.html |accessdate=February 11, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4sKaHkS |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref>  On March 16, 2010, ''Rock Band'' developer [[Harmonix]] released this version of the song (along with the original version) as downloadable content for the game.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Frushtick |first=Russ |url=http://multiplayerblog.mtv.com/2010/03/09/lady-gaga-finally-coming-to-rock-band/ |title=Lady Gaga Finally Coming To 'Rock Band' | publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=March 9, 2010 |accessdate=March 9, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4sMbXCE |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> In "W.T.F.", during an audition for the boys' professional wrestling league, one of the participants sings a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]-style number<U+2014>parodying the song "Nothing" from ''[[A Chorus Line]]''<U+2014>about why he wants to be a wrestler.<ref name="PWInsider" /> The episode "Fatbeard" received considerable press attention after Ike stated in a letter he would "vomit his balls out through his mouth" if he had to hear anything more about [[Susan Boyle]], the Scottish amateur singer who had recently gained worldwide attention for her performance of "[[I Dreamed a Dream]]" on ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]''.<ref name="Tucker0422" /><ref>{{Cite news |last=Lee |first=Cara |title=Susan Boyle makes South Park sick |work=[[The Sun (newspaper)|The Sun]] |date=April 23, 2009 |url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/tv/article2392316.ece |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4scjMFZ |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref>

==Reception==
===Critics===
{{Quote box |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=right |width=220px |align=right | quote  = From knocking celebrities off their high horse, to tackling social issues, to just plain pointing out the ridiculous nature of our every day lives, ''South Park'' Season 13 had more cultural impact than most animated series could ever dream of. Sure, it wasn't always great, and previous seasons have been better, but the series sure is doing well for its age. | source = <U+2014> Ramsley Isler, [[IGN]]<ref name="IGN1125" />}}
Ramsey Isler of [[IGN]] said ''South Park'' continued to be the "best animated comedy show on TV" during its thirteenth season. He said the season had some low points, particularly "Eat, Pray Queef", but that episodes like "The F Word" and "Dances with Smurfs" delivered significant social commentary. Isler described "Fishsticks" as a well-timed, hilarious episode that became a "phenomenon".<ref name="IGN1125">{{Cite web |last=Isler |first=Ramsey |title=South Park: Season 13 Review |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/104/1049514p1.html |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=November 25, 2009 |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4sfEDbk |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> Ben Flanagan of ''The Tuscaloosa News'' said the thirteenth season was one of the strongest yet for ''South Park'', and that the series continued its tradition of entertainingly combining gross-out comedy with social satire. He wrote, "Whether they tackle the Jonas Brothers, Somali pirates, Kanye West, ''The Dark Knight'', the current economic woes or just the frequent greed and foolishness of the human race, the show continues to solidify itself as not only the funniest show on TV, but the best."<ref name="Flanagan" />

Not all reviews of the season were positive. [[The A.V. Club|A.V. Club]] writer Sean O'Neal called it "one of the more hit-or-miss seasons of ''South Park'' in the show<U+2019>s history",<ref name="AVClub1118" /> but said he was confident the series could do better and that it had yet not entered the "staggering animal begging to be put out of its misery stage of a show's lifetime".<ref name="AVClub1118">{{Cite web |last=O'Neal |first=Sean |title=South Park: Pee |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=November 18, 2009 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/pee,35560/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qKJbFa |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> He described the season as a "weekly exercise in ''South Park'' schizophrenia", with some episodes faring better than others,<ref>{{Cite web |last=O'Neal |first=Sean |title=South Park: Butters' Bottom Bitch |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=October 15, 2009 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/butters-bottom-bitch,34140/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qOisPi |archivedate= November 7, 2010}}</ref> although he said the first half of the season was generally strong.<ref name="AVClub0422" /> Josh Modell, also of the A.V. Club, agreed that the season was uneven, with several episodes "you kinda shrugged your shoulders at",<ref name="Modell1021">{{Cite web |last=Modell |first=Josh |title=South Park: W.T.F. |date=October 21, 2009 |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/wtf,34408/ |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qRDEZc |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> but others like "Butters' Bottom Bitch" that he found "pretty damn funny".<ref name="Modell1021" />

"Fishsticks" particularly attracted  media attention,<ref name="IGN1125" /> and some critics declared it one of the best episodes of the season.<ref name="IGN1125" /><ref>{{Cite news |last=Brockington |first=Ryan |title=Kanye West Is Not a Gay Fish |work=[[New York Post]] |date=April 9, 2009|url=http://blogs.nypost.com/popwrap/archives/2009/04/kanye_west_fishsticks_gay.html |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qVqVqM |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> In the episode, Jimmy writes a joke that becomes a national sensation, while Cartman tries to steal the credit. A fictionalized version of rapper Kanye West fails to understand the joke. He cannot admit that he does not get it because, in reference to a perceived ego problem on the part of the real West, he considers himself a genius.<ref name="KW1">{{Cite news |last=Montgomery |first=James |title=Kanye West Responds -- Humbly! -- To 'South Park' 'Fish Sticks' Slam |publisher=MTV |date=April 9, 2009 |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1608939/20090409/west_kanye.jhtml |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qcqD5a |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name="KW2">{{Cite news |last=Dobuzinskis |first=Alex |title=Kanye West feels "murdered" by South Park swipe |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=April 10, 2009 |url=http://blogs.reuters.com/fanfare/2009/04/10/kanye-west-feels-murdered-by-south-park-swipe/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qfEI3d |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> On September 13, 2009, during the [[MTV Video Music Awards]], West interrupted an acceptance speech by country singer [[Taylor Swift]], walking on stage, grabbing the microphone and praising her competitor [[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles]].<ref name="VaryWest">{{Cite news |last=Vary |first=Adam B. |title="South Park" Kanye West "gay fish" episode to re-air |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=September 14, 2009 |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2009/09/14/south-park-kanye-west-gay-fish-episode/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qhbro9 |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Vozick-Levinson |first=Simon |title=Kanye West interrupts Taylor Swift's VMAs moment: What was he thinking? |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=September 13, 2009 |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/09/13/kanye-west-taylor-swift/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qjZcIO |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> The incident received considerable press coverage and, as a result, Comedy Central rebroadcast "Fishsticks" for two straight hours on September 15.<ref name="IGN1125" /><ref name="VaryWest" />

"The F Word" was especially controversial, even by ''South Park'' standards.<ref name="Seidman1110"/><ref name="Hibberd">{{Cite news |last=Hibberd |first=James |title=GLAAD protests "South Park" f-bomb episode |work=The Live Feed |date=November 5, 2009 |accessdate=February 18, 2010}}</ref> In the episode, the South Park boys attempt to change the official definition of the word "[[faggot (slang)|fag]]" from an [[homophobia|anti-homosexual]] slur to a term describing loud and obnoxious [[Harley-Davidson|Harley]] bikers. The uncensored word is voiced casually and very frequently throughout the episode. A.V. Club critic Genevieve Koski argued that the "The F Word" advocates a philosophy that language is ever-changing and that [[taboo]] words receive their stigma purely due to social circumstance.<ref name="AV1104">{{Cite web |last=Koski |first=Genevieve |title=South Park: The F Word |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=November 4, 2009 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-f-word,35013/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qlqBc0 |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> Although some [[LGBT]] activists accepted that the episode had noble intentions, the [[Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]] nevertheless objected to it, claiming that it still used "fag" as a means of insulting others and could be unintentionally harmful to the gay community.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Itzkoff |first=Dave |title=Gay Advocacy Group Objects to "South Park" Episode |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 6, 2009 |url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/11/06/gay-advocacy-group-objects-to-south-park-episode/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qoWaya |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Michael A. |title=Should South Park Get Away With Using the F-Word? |publisher=Gay Rights |date=November 6, 2009 |url=http://gayrights.change.org/blog/view/should_south_park_get_away_with_using_the_f-word |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qr1NOY |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> Some critics praised the episode and said it addressed an important and difficult issue,<ref name="Hibberd" /> whereas others felt the satire was ineffective and unfunny.<ref name="AV1104" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Isler |first=Ramsey |title=South Park: "The F Word" Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=November 5, 2009 |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/104/1042445p1.html |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qssdA9 |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref>

===Celebrity reactions===
[[File:Kanyewestdec2008.jpg|right|thumb|180 px|[[Kanye West]], spoofed in "Fishsticks", wrote in his blog that the episode was funny, although it hurt his feelings.|alt=A man wearing sunglasses, blue jeans, a gray sweatshirt and an orange vest with tiger-stripes designs performs on a stage into an orange microphone.]]
Some celebrities who were spoofed in thirteenth season episodes responded to their portrayals. The day after "Fishsticks" aired, West wrote on his blog, "South Park murdered me last night and it's pretty damn funny. It hurts my feelings but what can you expect from South Park!" West thanked the ''South Park'' writers in his blog entry and acknowledged he has a problem with his ego, but said he was trying to change.<ref>{{Cite news |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=April 9, 2009 |title=Kanye West responds to 'South Park' mockery |last=Vozick-Levinson |first=Simon |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/04/09/kanye-south-par/ |accessdate=November 1, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4qvhSaY |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name="Kreps">{{Cite news |last=Kreps |first=Daniel |title=Kanye West Admits to Getting "Murdered" by "South Park," Promises to Deflate Ego |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=April 9, 2009}}</ref> The blog post drew substantial media attention; Daniel Kreps of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' said: "Many have tried, all have failed, but in the end it only took four animated children from Colorado to topple Kanye West's ego."<ref name="Kreps" /> [[Carlos Mencia]], host of the Comedy Central show ''[[Mind of Mencia]]'', was also spoofed in "Fishsticks". He is portrayed as knowingly stealing credit for a joke he did not write, which is a reference to accusations other comedians have made that Mencia plagiarizes jokes from other people.<ref name="Itzkoff0409">{{Cite news |last=Itzkoff |first=Dave |title=Carlos Mencia Responds to "South Park" |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 9, 2009 |url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/04/09/carlos-mencia-responds-to-south-park/ |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/mainframe.php |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Top Moments: Scantily Clad Cops, Bad Pick-Up Lines, and Other Rites of Spring |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=April 10, 2009 |url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/kutner-dies-house-1004945.aspx |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4r3mhCp |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> After the episode aired, Mencia wrote on his [[Twitter]] feed, "They just made fun of me on South Park. I thought it was hysterical. Catch the rerun."<ref name="Itzkoff0409" />

In "The Coon", Butters suspects heavyset comedian [[Bruce Vilanch]] is Cartman's superhero alter ego based on his physique. After the episode aired, Vilanch sent a card to Parker and Stone thanking them for referring to him.<ref>{{Cite video | people=[[Trey Parker|Parker, Trey]]| date=November 2010 |title=South Park: The Complete Thirteenth Season: "The Coon" |format=Audio commentary |medium= Blu-ray Disc|publisher=[[Paramount Pictures#Paramount Home Entertainment|Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Shortly after "Whale Whores" aired, Paul Watson said he was not offended by his portrayal in the episode, and was glad ''South Park'' brought the issue of dolphin and whale slaughter, and the Japanese role in it, to a large audience.<ref>{{Cite web |last=d'Estries |first=Michael |title=South Park <U+201C>Whale Whores<U+201D>: Captain Paul Watson Responds |date=October 30, 2009 |publisher=ecorazzi |url=http://www.ecorazzi.com/2009/10/30/south-park-whale-whores-captain-paul-watson-responds/ |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4r5zkeI |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> After Billy Mays appeared in "Dead Celebrities", his son Billy Mays III said he loved the episode and found its portrayal of his father tasteful and respectful.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=MJ Morning Show: 10/9/2009 |series=The MJ Morning Show |serieslink=The MJ Morning Show |credits=Mays III, Billy |network=[[WFLZ-FM]] |city=[[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], [[Florida]] |airdate=October 9, 2009}}</ref> [[Jason Hawes]] and [[Grant Wilson]], the stars of ''[[Ghost Hunters]]'' who were also mocked in "Dead Celebrities", said they loved the parody and encouraged fans to watch the show on their Twitter accounts.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sagers |first=Aaron |title=Syfy 'Ghost Hunters': Living Normally Within Paranormal Pop Culture |publisher=[[PopMatters]] |date=October 29, 2009 |url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/feature/115513-syfy-ghost-hunters-living-normally-within-paranormal-pop-culture/ |accessdate=February 24, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4r9aITK |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> The day after "Dances with Smurfs" originally aired, Glenn Beck discussed the episode on his [[Glenn Beck Program|radio program]] and said he took the parody as a compliment.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=November 12, 2009 |series=Glenn Beck Program |serieslink=Glenn Beck Program |credits=[[Glenn Beck|Beck, Glenn]]; [[Steve Burguiere|Burguiere, Steve]]; [[Pat Gray|Gray, Pat]] |network=[[Premiere Radio Networks]] |station=[[Radio City Music Hall]] |city=[[New York City]] |airdate=November 12, 2009 |began=1:40 p.m. |ended=1:50 p.m.}}</ref> The Jonas Brothers' publicist specifically forbade reporters from asking the band members about their portrayal in "The Ring". Nevertheless, [[Nick Jonas]] said, "We are always open to make fun of ourselves."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sperounes |first=Sandra |title=Can life get any more awesome? Yes, if you're one of the Jonas Brothers. |publisher=[[Canwest News Service]] |date=March 13, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last=Abbott | first=Jim | date=March 18, 2009 | title = Jonas Brothers talk about tour, TV show and the fans | url = http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_music_blog/2009/03/jonas-brothers-talk-about-tour-tv-show-and-the-fans.html | work = [[Orlando Sentinel]] | accessdate = February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4rIRsEJ |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref>

"Pinewood Derby" drew considerable media attention in Mexico when it first aired due to its depiction of Mexican President [[Felipe Calder<U+00F3>n]].<ref name="bbc news">{{cite web |last=Miglierini |first=Julian |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/8507514.stm |title=MTV under fire as it pulls South Park episode in Mexico |accessdate=February 10, 2010 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=February 10, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4rKdru6 |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> The episode was due to air in Spanish on [[MTV Latin America]] on February 8, 2010, but it was pulled a few hours before the scheduled time. Media reports indicated the decision stemmed from the episode's depiction of Calder<U+00F3>n irritating the international community and frivolously spending alien-provided "space cash" on water parks.<ref name="bbc news" /><ref>{{Cite news |title=MTV no emite episodio de South Park y Calder<U+00F3>n" Review |date=February 9, 2010 |work=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]] |language=Spanish |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/657349.html |accessdate=February 9, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/657349.html |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> MTV said the ''South Park'' creators did not get a special permit needed to broadcast an image of Mexico's flag, but the explanation was met with skepticism by Mexican ''South Park'' fans, some of whom accused MTV of censorship.<ref name="bbc news" />

"Fatbeard" included prominent references to the [[Maersk Alabama hijacking|April 2009 hijacking]] of the [[MV Maersk Alabama|MV ''Maersk Alabama'']] by Somalian pirates. The crew of the [[USS Bainbridge (DDG-96)|USS ''Bainbridge'']], the [[Arleigh Burke class destroyer|''Arleigh Burke''<U+2013>class]] guided-missile destroyer that participated in the rescue of [[Richard Phillips (captain)|Richard Phillips]] from ''Maersk Alabama'', contacted the ''South Park'' creators to commend them on the episode. Ensign Jonathan Sieg, the ''Bainbridge'' public relations officer, wrote, "Pretty much everyone onboard our ship<U+2014>from Captain to seaman<U+2014>is a huge fan of ''South Park'', and when we heard about the episode 'Fatbeard', as you can imagine, we were thrilled and very interested to watch."<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/fans/faq/355082|title=FAQ - South Park Studios |publisher=[[South Park|South Park Studios]] |date=May 15, 2009 |accessdate=February 20, 2010}}</ref>

===Ratings===
The thirteenth season of ''South Park'' generally maintained the average [[Nielsen rating]] viewership for the series, around 3&nbsp;million viewers per episode.<ref name="CC0827" /> The season premiere, "The Ring", was seen in 3.41&nbsp;million households. That would prove to be the largest individual viewership for any Comedy Central show that season, outperforming even a highly anticipated and publicized episode of ''[[The Daily Show]]'' involving [[Jon Stewart's 2009 criticism of CNBC|Jon Stewart's ongoing feud]] with [[CNBC]] and pundit [[Jim Cramer]].<ref name="RingRate"/> The thirteenth season of ''South Park'' received its lowest viewership in the episodes "Dances with Smurfs", seen in 1.47&nbsp;million households;<ref name="SmurfRate"/> "W.T.F.", seen in 1.37&nbsp;million households;<ref name="WTFRate" /> and "The F Word", seen in 1.99&nbsp;million households.<ref name="Seidman1110"/> However, "The F Word" was the highest rated show of the season among viewers between ages 18 and 49,<ref name="Seidman1110" /> and outperformed ''[[The Jay Leno Show]]'', [[NBC]]'s primetime talk show.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Strong |first=H.T. |title=SOUTH PARK Beats JAY LENO!! World Series Best In Five Years!! Big Number For Petite MODEL!! Lotsa Season Lows!! |publisher=[[Ain't It Cool News]] |date=November 5, 2009 |url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/42986 |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4soB9cw |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> The season finale, "Pee", was seen in 2.87&nbsp;million households, which made it the most watched cable show of the night.<ref name="PeeRate"/> Likewise, "The Coon", seen in 3.27&nbsp;million households, was the most watched cable program among ages 18 to 49 the week it aired.<ref name="CoonRate"/> Several episodes from the thirteenth season of ''South Park'' were the most watched Comedy Central shows the week they aired, including "Margaritaville" (2.77&nbsp;million households),<ref name="MargRate"/> "Fatbeard" (2.59&nbsp;million households),<ref name="FatRate"/> "Eat, Pray, Queef" (3&nbsp;million households)<ref name="EPQRate"/> and "Fishsticks" (3.1&nbsp;million households).<ref name="FishRate"/> The latter two episodes were watched by over 1&nbsp;million more viewers than the network's second-highest-rated shows in their respective weeks.<ref name="EPQRate" /><ref name="FishRate" />

===Awards===
Parker and Stone decided to submit "Margaritaville" for an [[Emmy Award]] because they had received a large amount of positive feedback about the episode from adult viewers. Since most Emmy voters are older, they decided "Margaritaville" stood the best chance of winning. Stone joked, "If an Emmy voter were to watch this, they might think the show was smarter than it was, so they might be fooled into voting for us."<ref>{{Cite video | people=[[Matt Stone|Stone, Matt]]| date=November 2010 |title=South Park: The Complete Thirteenth Season: "Margaritaville" |format=Audio commentary |medium=Blu-ray Disc|publisher=[[Paramount Pictures#Paramount Home Entertainment|ParamountHome Entertainment]]}}</ref> "Margaritaville" ultimately won the 2009 Emmy Award for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program (for Programming Less Than One Hour)|Outstanding Animated Program for Programming Less Than One Hour]] against competing nominees ''[[Robot Chicken]]'', ''[[The Simpsons]]'' and ''[[American Dad]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |work=[[Emmy Award|Emmys.com]] |date=July 16, 2009 |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |url=http://www.emmys.com/category/nomination-category/outstanding-animated-program-programming-less-one-hour?page=4 |title=Outstanding Animated Program (for programming less than one hour |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4svFdGK |archivedate=November 7, 2010)}}</ref> The victory marked the third consecutive Emmy win for ''South Park'', which won in the same category in 2007 for the [[South Park (season 10)|tenth season]] episode "[[Make Love, Not Warcraft]]", and won the award for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program (for Programming One Hour or More)|Outstanding Animated Program for Programming One Hour or More]] for the [[South Park (season 11)|eleventh season]] episode "[[Imaginationland Episode I|Imaginationland]]".<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tina Fey, Justin Timberlake Among Big Creative Arts Winners |date=September 12, 2009 |publisher=[[Emmy Award|Emmys.com]] |url=http://www.emmys.com/articles/hbo-tops-2009-creative-arts-emmys-nbc-leads-nets |accessdate=February 20, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4t17IyX |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> Parker, Stone, Agnone, Stough, Beard, Howell, Rivinoja, Chatman, Hader and Quincy were all recipients of the Emmy.<ref name="EmmyWinners" />

In February 2010, "Whale Whores" was nominated for a [[Genesis Awards|Genesis Award]] in the television comedy category. The Genesis Awards honor news and entertainment media for outstanding work that raises public understanding of animal issues. "Whale Whores" ultimately lost to the ''[[Family Guy]]'' episode "[[Dog Gone]]."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.humanesociety.org/about/events/genesis_awards/nominees.html |publisher=[[The Humane Society of the United States]] |title=Nominees for the Genesis Awards |publisher=[[Humane Society]] |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5uDcStKnm |archivedate=March 26, 2010}}</ref>

==Home release==
The season was released by [[Paramount Pictures#Paramount Home Entertainment|Paramount Home Entertainment]] in the United States on March 16, 2010, on both [[DVD]] (as a three-disc set) and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] (as a two-disc set). Each set included all fourteen uncensored episodes in [[1080p]] video and [[Dolby TrueHD]] sound, as well as brief audio commentaries by Parker and Stone for each episode,<ref>{{cite web|last=Foster |first=Dave |url=http://www.dvdtimes.co.uk/content.php?contentid=71969 |title=South Park Season 13 (R1/US BD) in March |publisher=Thedigitalfix.co.uk |date=December 14, 2009 |accessdate=February 24, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4t6LtrG |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref> seven deleted scenes, codes for unlocking a character and challenge levels in ''[[South Park Let's Go Tower Defense Play!]]'' on [[Xbox Live Arcade]], and a special mini-feature, ''Inside Xbox: A Behind-the-Scenes Tour of South Park Studios'', describing the show's animation process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/shop/dvds/season13/|publisher=Southparkstudios.com|title=The Complete Thirteenth Season|quote=[http://www.southparkstudios.com/layout/dvds/img/pages/season13/specialFeaturesPromo.png see image]|accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=South Park: The Complete Thirteenth Season Blu-ray Review |publisher=Blu-ray.com |date=March 5, 2010 |last=Liebman |first=Martin |url=http://www.Blu-ray.com/movies/South-Park-The-Complete-Thirteenth-Season-Blu-ray-Review/8807/ |accessdate=March 25, 2010 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5u4t8vniO |archivedate=November 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.craveonline.com/entertainment/tv/article/south-park-season-13-dvd-review-98671|title=South Park Season 13 DVD Review|date=March 21, 2010|first=Johnny|last=Firecloud|publisher=Crave Online|accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref>

